<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-246-038 </DOCNO><DOCID>09 774 487</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Jan 8 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Datapoint gets new president. (Datapoint Corp. names John Harrisonpresident after Michael Michigami resigns)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wood, Lamont.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Datapoint Corp. (Officials and employees).andO;Ticker:    DPT.andO;Topic:     Facility RelocationExecutiveRetirementHiringComputer industry.andO;Person:    Michigami, Michael (Resignation, retirement, etc.); Harrison, John(Selection and appointment).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>DATAPOINT GETS NEW PRESIDENT 01/08/91 SAN ANTONIO, TEXAS, U.S.A., 1991 JAN 8(NB) -- After returning Datapoint to profitability and being re-elected tothe board just three weeks ago, Michael Michigami has resigned as presidentof Datapoint, saying family obligations prevent him from moving to Paris.andM;Datapoint had announced last month that its headquarters would be moved toParis, where the firm does 80 percent of its business and chairman AsherEdelman operates.andP;  Only top executives will be moved, with other operationsremaining in San Antonio.andM;&quot;Datapoint accepts Michael's resignation with regret, as he has made asignificant contribution during his tenure by stabilizing revenues, reducingoperating expenses and maintaining customer and employee confidence during adifficult period,&quot; Edelman announced.andP;  &quot;We respect his personal commitmentsand understand the reasons for his resignation.andM;Michigami is being replaced by John Harrison, a British citizen with 32 yearsof experience in the computer industry, including 20 in the Europeanoperations of Sperry Corp. He has been a consultant with Datapoint, workingon formulating a &quot;strategic operating plan&quot; since August 1990.andM;Michigami, who became president in August 1989, is the fourth Datapointpresident to resign since Edelman made a successful hostile takeover of thefirm in 1985.andP;  The company has been beset with declining revenues,restructuring costs, and further hostile takeover attempts.andM;Although the firm lost $29.2 million in fiscal 1989 and $82.8 million infiscal 90, it made a profit in the first quarter of fiscal 1991 (endingOctober 27, 1990), making $3.1 million on revenues of $58.5 million.andO;However, revenue was down about $2 million from the same quarter last year.andM;(Lamont Wood/19910108/Press Contact: Tom Drohan, Datapoint, 203/651-9987)</TEXT></DOC>